## üí¨ EVIDENCE INTEGRATION

Despite the incomplete statistical analysis, the curated evidence provides critical insights into the nature of populist and nationalist discourse within the corpus. These examples illustrate the framework's ability to identify relevant linguistic markers.

The prevalence of populist appeals is evident across various administrations and document types. For instance, the framing of "the people" against an "establishment" is a recurring theme. Donald Trump's rhetoric frequently employed such language, stating, "For decades, a radical and corrupt establishment has extracted power and wealth from our citizens while the pillars of our society lay broken and seemingly in complete disrepair" [2]. He also emphasized unity under a singular agenda: "The agenda I will lay out this evening is not a Republican agenda or a Democrat agenda. It's the agenda of the American people" [3]. More recently, a declaration of national resurgence stated, "America is back... Our spirit is back. Our pride is back. Our confidence is back. And the American Dream is surging bigger and better than ever before" [4]. These statements align with the framework's definition of populist discourse, characterized by anti-elite sentiment and direct appeals to the populace.

Similarly, the Democratic Party Platform of 1992 called for a "revolution in government, to take power away from entrenched bureaucracies and narrow interests in Washington and put it back in the hands of ordinary people" [5], showcasing a consistent thread of populist framing within party platforms.

The corpus also displays distinct nationalist sentiments. The Democratic Platform of 2016, for example, explicitly adopted a nationalist slogan: "America First. It‚Äôs not just a slogan, it‚Äôs a principle. We will put American jobs, American workers, and American security before anything else" [6]. This exemplifies the framework's nationalism dimension, emphasizing national interest and potentially signaling a shift towards more pronounced nationalist rhetoric in certain contexts.

